---
/**
 * /about — the second-touch brand page (SUR-520).
 *
 * Home for the longer-form positioning that SUR-479 deliberately kept off the
 * tight landing page. Structure:
 *   - Lede: the three "What Surfc is" paragraphs, lifted verbatim from
 *     WhatSurfcIs.astro (LP keeps its own copy; the two diverge over time).
 *   - "Why I built Surfc": the founder essay (single-column centrepiece).
 *   - Manifesto: the PulledQuote.astro preserved-but-unused since SUR-479.
 *   - Closing CTA: reused unchanged.
 *
 * Deferred sections (positioning → SUR-510; expanded E2EE → SUR-117) are left
 * as commented scaffolding for those tickets. The Adler/lineage rec is covered
 * narratively by the essay, so no separate Lineage section is scaffolded.
 *
 * Adopts the landing page's front-door identity via `front-door-surface` on the
 * bodyClass: EB Garamond display headings + Sometype Mono body. This unifies the
 * lede and the essay under one body face and matches index.astro (SUR-508), so
 * the page no longer mixes Inter and serif bodies across sections.
 * Page-specific layout lives in src/styles/about.css (cf. pricing.astro).
 */

import BaseLayout  from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import Nav         from '../components/Nav.astro'
import PulledQuote from '../components/PulledQuote.astro'
import ClosingCta  from '../components/ClosingCta.astro'
import Footer      from '../components/Footer.astro'

import '../styles/about.css'
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Surfc"
  description="Surfc is the idea index that turns a lifetime of marked books into searchable, end-to-end-encrypted thoughts; filed under the idea, not the book."
  path="/about/"
  noindex={true}
  bodyClass="lp-page-v2 front-door-surface"
>
  <Nav />
  <main id="main">
    <!-- Lede — three "What Surfc is" paragraphs, verbatim from WhatSurfcIs.astro -->
    <section id="about-lede" class="hiw-section-v2 about-lede">
      <h1 class="hiw-h2 hiw-h2-hero hiw-h2-center">About Surfc</h1>
      <div class="about-lede__body">
        <p class="hiw-body-v2">
          You've highlighted hundreds of passages. You can't find them when
          you need them. Surfc is the private idea index that gets you from a
          marked book to a searchable thought — without having to remember
          which book it was in.
        </p>
        <p class="hiw-body-v2">
          Most reading tools file your highlights under the book. Surfc files
          them under the idea — so when you go looking for what you read
          about authority, or memory, or trust, the book follows the thought.
        </p>
        <p class="hiw-body-v2">
          Your notes and AI insights are protected with end-to-end encryption
          at rest, including synced storage.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why I built Surfc — founder essay (the long-form centrepiece) -->
    <section id="why-i-built-surfc" class="hiw-section-v2 about-essay">
      <div class="about-essay__inner">
        <h2 class="hiw-h2 hiw-h2-center">Why I built Surfc</h2>

        <p>
          Reading is a strange kind of investment. You pour years into it,
          hundreds of books, thousands of hours, and the returns are real but
          almost impossible to point to. I can feel the books that changed me.
          I cannot always name them. Something I read years ago rearranged how
          I think about a thing I now treat as obvious, and if you asked me
          which book, which chapter, which sentence did the work, I would have
          nothing for you. The change took. The receipt did not.
        </p>
        <p>
          That bothers me more than it probably should. You like to believe you
          remember what shaped you. You don't, not really. You remember a vague
          glow around a title, a feeling that a book mattered, and almost none
          of the substance that did the actual shaping. The insight was there,
          it did its work, and then it slipped quietly out the back while you
          were busy starting the next book.
        </p>
        <p>
          And that is the generous version, the one where the idea at least
          left a mark. The everyday frustration is smaller and more annoying
          than that. I know I read something good about a topic. I go looking
          for it. It isn't anywhere. It is underlined in a book on a shelf I
          haven't opened in three years, or scribbled in a margin I will never
          find again, or highlighted in some app that swallowed it whole.
          Hundreds of passages I cared enough to mark, and not one of them
          within reach the moment I actually need it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The part nobody wants to admit is that highlighting is not keeping.
          Marking a passage feels like saving it. It isn't. It is the reading
          equivalent of photographing a meal instead of tasting it, a gesture
          toward memory that quietly stands in for the memory itself. A
          highlight you cannot retrieve, cannot connect, cannot argue with
          months later is just ink on a page (which, when you say it plainly
          like that, is a slightly depressing thing to have done a thousand
          times).
        </p>
        <p>
          So I built the thing I actually wanted. Not a place to dump
          highlights. An index. Somewhere a note I make today finds the note I
          made years ago, where the ideas I keep circling back to surface on
          their own instead of waiting for me to remember they exist. And, this
          is the part that matters most to me, somewhere I can see not just what
          I nodded along with but what I argued against. The agreements are
          easy. The tensions are where the change actually happens. You don't
          really take an idea on board until you have wrestled with it, and I
          wanted a record of the wrestling, not just the verdict it ended on.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is Surfc. It started, as a lot of this did, with Adler. I was
          finishing <em>How to Read a Book</em> and I had this sinking feeling
          that everything I was learning, every insight the book had set off in
          me, would start eroding the second I slid it back onto the shelf. I
          did not want a reading app. I have plenty of those. I wanted a private
          record of the person I am becoming through the things I have read and
          the thoughts I have kept, mine to hold, and worth more the longer I
          keep at it.
        </p>
        <p>
          I built it for myself first, and I will not pretend otherwise. But it
          turns out I am not the only one. There are other people who read to
          think, who argue in the margins, who want a lifetime of reading to
          compound instead of scatter across shelves and apps and forgotten
          highlights. If that is you, then somewhere along the way I started
          building it for you too.
        </p>

        <p class="about-essay__sign">— Deji Dipeolu</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Manifesto — the PulledQuote preserved (but unused) since SUR-479 -->
    <PulledQuote />

    {/* TODO SUR-510: <section id="what-it-isnt"> What it is / what it isn't */}
    {/* TODO SUR-117 expansion: <section id="why-e2ee"> Why E2EE matters */}
    {/* No separate Lineage section — the essay above covers the Adler heritage. */}

    <ClosingCta />
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
